        <Parent_String>casters (vessels) [300043027], condiment vessels [300198282], vessels for serving and consuming food [300198938], containers for serving and consuming food [300198760], culinary containers [300197577], containers by function or context [300197200], containers (receptacles) [300197197], Containers (hierarchy name) [300045611], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Casters intended primarily for serving table sugar, usually of baluster or cylindrical shape with a pierced domed cover, which was sometimes screwed to the container. Used especially for such vessels that were historically used as part of a set at table. For larger vessels used for sprinkling table sugar or powdered sugar in the kitchen, as opposed to at table, use "sugar shakers." For larger vessels having a wide spout or opening used for pouring sugar, use "sugar dispensers."</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079898/Wees, English, Irish, and Scottish Silver (1997)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Espolvoreadores para servir principalmente azúcar en la mesa, generalmente en forma de balaustre o cilíndricos con una cubierta abovedada y perforada, la cual algunas veces se atornillaba a la vasija. </Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Strooiers die met name bedoeld zijn voor het serveren van suiker op tafel, meestal cylinder- of balustervormig met een geperforeerd, bol deksel dat soms op de strooier zelf moet worden geschroefd.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052381/Van Dale Engels-Nederlands (1989)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Streuer, der hauptsächlich zum Servieren von Zucker gedacht ist, gewöhnlich in Baluster- oder Zylinderform mit einer gelochten Wölbkappe, die manchmal mit dem Behälter verschraubt wird.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
